The plot of the “ Menaechmi '’ turns upon mistaken identity in the case of twin brothers. One of them, while still a child, had been stolen from his father and taken to Epidamnus3 the other twin, when he arrived at manhood‚ came from Syracuse to Epidamnus in search of his brother. The two are constantly mis- taken‚ the one for the other, by the friends of each, until in the last. act the two happen on the stage to- gether, and the mystery is solved. The plot is of special interest to the English reader, as having sug- gested that of Shakspeare's “Comedy of Errors.” The “argument ’⁹ preceding the text of the ‘⁶ Menaechmi ” was probably not written by Plautus. It appears to have been added at a much later time, Ritschl thinks in the second century A.D.
